entry.title: Remove FencedFrameConfig URL attribute
entry.content:
We're removing what we colloquially refer to as "default mode" in fenced

frames, which is where you manually construct a `new

FencedFrameConfig()` object with a (usually) non-opaque URL, to use

fenced frames without relying on cross-site data from FLEDGE or Shared

Storage. If a use-case that requires this mode of fenced frames presents

itself in the future, we will re-add it. But for now, this entails:

1. Removing the FencedFrameConfig#url IDL attribute

- Handled by this CL

- See corresponding spec change:

https://github.com/WICG/fenced-frame/pull/88

2. Removing the FencedFrameConfig web-exposed constructor

- This will happen in a subsequent CL



We're removing the URL attribute of the FencedFrameConfig interface [1] because if fenced frames can only be used with FLEDGE/Shared Storage,

the URL member is always "opaque", since the true value depends on

cross-site data. An always "opaque"-returning attribute does not add any

value to web developers.



To carry out this change we must remove tests that rely on observing

the FencedFrameConfig#url attribute, as these tests will need to be

removed anyways when fully removing "default mode".



[1]: https://wicg.github.io/fenced-frame/#fenced-frame-config-interface



R=gtanzer@chromium.org

entry.title: Add FilteredReportQueue to deduplicate events.
entry.content:
Declare FilteredReportQueue with Filter that can be used to accept or

reject events on the way to Enqueue. One of the possibilities is for

Filter subclass to keep track of previously enqueued event(s) and reject

the new one if it (partially) repeats what was enqueued before, or if

the new event is coming too soon after the previous one.



As opposed to rate limiting, it seems preferable to do it on top of

ReportQueue, so that we don't need to deserialize events for

filtering/comparing them (if it was done inside ReportQueue, it would be

too late for that: the events would already be serilalized).

entry.title: Fix unexpected NTP navigations in <webview> guests.
entry.content:
guests cannot be navigated to chrome: URLs or, more

generally, to schemes that aren't web-safe. The guest's embedder

typically enforces this in WebViewGuest::LoadURLWithParams(),

replacing such navigations with navigations to about:blank and

dispatching abort events.



However, we noticed crashes in the wild that indicated that guests

were nonetheless being navigated to WebUI URLs, which triggered

various check failures in //content, including [1] and [2].



The source of these attempts turned out to be in the security

interstitial code. If an interstitial is being dismissed via the

"Back to safety" button, and there's nothing in history to go back to,

this code would instead navigate to a "known-safe page", which in most

cases is the chrome://newtab NTP URL chrome::kChromeUINewTabURL). This

is a WebUI URL which cannot be loaded in a guest WebContents.



Given that guests may show security interstitials for now (this

support may soon go away as part of refactoring guests for MPArch, see

extensions_features::kWebviewTagMPArchBehavior), this CL tweaks the

known safe page to just be about:blank for guests. It also adds

defense-in-depth logic inside //content to cancel any attempts to load

unsafe URLs in guests before they hit the subsequent checks.



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:content/browser/renderer_host/render_frame_host_impl.cc;l=5999;drc=06fc8248742880e9e9fb639a8f57099d28ffd7b7



[2] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/refs/heads/main:content/browser/renderer_host/render_frame_host_impl.cc;l=10270;drc=9c68f2c46912577bf73bcf032c0f8c00379a0bca

entry.title: multipaste: Stop Ctrl+V longpress pastes from being discarded in Lacros
entry.content:
This CL fixes a Lacros bug where selecting an item from a clipboard

history menu shown by Ctrl+V longpress would not paste anything. This

bug is caused by the exo keyboard interpreting clipboard history's

synthetic Ctrl+V paste event as a repeat of the Ctrl+V events that

pulled up the menu, because it is not guaranteed that the user would

release the longpress before selecting a clipboard history item.



This CL addresses the issue by having the clipboard history controller

issue an extra Ctrl+V release before the press and release meant to

paste the selected item. A preferable long-term solution would be for

clipboard history pastes to use surface-specific text insertion APIs

rather than synthesizing Ctrl+V, but this is not feasible in the scope

of the current project.



Note: Tast testing will be added if this feature makes it past dogfood.

entry.title: Add PrivateAggregation.BudgetStorage.BeginInitializationCount metric
entry.content:
Count the number of times the budget storage begins initialization. This

metric is intended to be used in conjunction with the

"PrivacySandbox.PrivateAggregation.BudgetStorage.ShutdownBeforeFinishingInitialization"

metric, which does not measure cases where the browser is shut down

abruptly. This is being added following the budgeter's storage becoming

lazily initialized (crrev.com/c/4534698) to measure the incidence of

operations being dropped due to this initialization not being completed

before (abrupt) shutdown.



To get the actual number of times the browser is shut down before

finishing initialization, including cases where shut down abruptly,

subtract the count of true "ShutdownBeforeFinishingInitialization" from

this metric's total count.

entry.content:
Specifically if enough canvases have had acceleration disabled then

newly created canvases will start out with acceleration disabled.

The behavior is controlled by two params. When this feature is

enabled, a newly created canvas will start with acceleration

disabled if the following two requirements are met (per Document);

1. More than `kCanvasDisableAccelerationThresholdParam` canvases have

been created.

2. The percent of canvases with acceleration disabled is >=

`kCanvasDisableAccelerationPercentParam`.

entry.title: [Read Anything] Pass copy command to main page
entry.content:
Before this change, users can copy text from the reading mode webui

using keyboard shortcuts (Ctrl+C on Windows, Cmd+C on Mac). This

allowed users to copy text to their clipboard even if the main web

page disabled copying.



In this CL, copy commands are disabled from the reading mode webui side

and are instead passed to the active web contents to be handled. This

way, Ctrl+C on the webui will have the same effect as Ctrl+C on the

main webpage. If Ctrl+C is disabled, then nothing will be copied to the

clipboard.

entry.title: Unify AutofillProfile table layout.
entry.content:
kLocalOrSyncable and kAccount profiles are currently stored in sets of

tables with different layouts. This makes maintenance more difficult.

This CL migrates kLocalOrSyncable profiles to a new set of tables which

share the same layout as the kAccount profiles. See design doc in the

bug for more details.



This CL does several things, which sadly can't be split well:

- Create the new tables: local_profiles and local_profiles_type_tokens.

Since Sync support for kLocalOrSyncable profiles is about to be

sunset, "syncable" is not part of the table name.

- In the database migration logic, copy all existing kLocalOrSyncable

profiles from the old tables to the new ones. This is tested in

web_database_migration_unittest.cc.

- Adapt the AutofillTable CRUD functions to read/write from the new set

of tables. This amounts to parameterizing the existing reading/writing

functions for kAccount profiles. No new logic is added.

For this purpose, two helper functions GetProfileMetadataTable() and

GetProfileTypeTokensTable() are introduced. Since the unit tests are

already parameterized by profile source, no large changes are

necessary.

Much of the old logic that writes to the legacy tables becomes unused

and is removed. The reading functions are kept for the migration

logic.

`shared-autofill` is enabled and either

- the target origin is the main frame's origin and value to filled is

non-sensitive, or

- the triggered origin is the main frame's origin.

entry.content:
The domWindow() method of the Document class can potentially return nullptr

as noted in renderer/core/dom/document.h



> // A document may or may not have a browsing context

> // (https://html.spec.whatwg.org/#browsing-context). A document with a browsing

> // context is created by navigation, and has a non-null domWindow(), GetFrame(),

> // Loader(), etc., and is visible to the user. It will have a valid

> // GetExecutionContext(), which will be equal to domWindow(). If the Document

> // constructor receives a DocumentInit created WithDocumentLoader(), it will

> // have a browsing context.

> // Documents created by all other APIs do not have a browsing context. These

> // Documents still have a valid GetExecutionContext() (i.e., the domWindow() of

> // the Document in which they were created), so they can still access

> // script, but return null for domWindow(), GetFrame() and Loader(). Generally,

> // they should not downcast the ExecutionContext to a LocalDOMWindow and access

> // the properties of the window directly.



Upon checking further, the offending document returns null for GetFrame() and

Loader() aswell so this was likely just an oversight and no invariants are being

violated



Introduced in https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4202152



More details https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1447388

entry.title: Change clock drift samples distance to 1h
entry.content:
This CL does not have any functional consequences, it just decreases

noise of data we collect from clients in some UMA histograms.



Latency variance is currently a very large confounding factor for

analyzing the identifiable information leaked by the clock drift of

the user. Typical clock drift values lie around 1ms/s which means that

latency variances beyond 1ms2 will make the drift data completely

unreliable.



In this CL we change the distance between the clock skew samples used

for the computation of the drift to be 1h apart. This way, latency

variances in the order of milliseconds square will play a much

smaller role.

entry.title: Add switch to turn on 3P cookie blocking from command line
entry.content:
This switch is intended for testing purposes only and is not meant to

be enabled in production. It allows developers to test their sites

in order to adopt Privacy Sandbox APIs meant to replace third-party

cookies.



For now, the switch just enables 3PC blocking at startup and

overrides any changes to the 3P cookie blocking content setting.

Site-specific content settings can override this switch, which should

allow cookie access due to SAA.



When 3P cookie blocking is enabled, some Privacy Sandbox APIs are

disabled (e.g. FedCM). This is acceptable for now, but we should

iterate on this switch to enable these purpose-driven APIs and still

disables third-party cookie tracking.
